    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-04-07T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-04-07T12:00:00-05:00" n="678"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d678">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">357.AB/4–752: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Pakistan</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_WAM1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Warren</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d678fn1">This telegram was repeated for information to
                        London.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Karachi</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-04-07T22:00:00+05:00"
                            >April 7, 1952—10 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1154. <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 1018, April 5, 5 p.m. <gloss
                        target="#t_FonMin1">FonMin</gloss> this afternoon said his first personal
                    reaction to the <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss>’s suggestion is that it
                    may be worthwhile if there is hope that <persName corresp="#p_GDF1"
                        >Graham</persName> wld come to grips with the problem. Evidence of such
                    intent wld be inclusion of military advisors in the group conducting the
                    conversations. Either Devers, Malone, Clay or Wedemeyer will be acceptable to
                        <gloss target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss>s. Shld this foregoing thought be
                    acceptable to <persName corresp="#p_GDF1">Graham</persName> and the <gloss
                        target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss>, the <gloss target="#t_FonMin1">FonMin</gloss>
                    is confident that the <gloss target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss> Cab wld be willing to
                    send a cab min to the <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss>—probably
                        <persName>Mahmoud Hussein</persName>, Min for Kashmiri Affairs—supported by
                    advisors who wld probably include the <gloss target="#t_fon1">Fon</gloss> Secy
                    and the Secy of Defense.</p>
                <p>The <gloss target="#t_FonMin1">FonMin</gloss> will not leave <gloss
                        target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss> at this time because he is needed to guide the
                    Cab thinking and to act as a brake on precipitate action.</p>
                <p>The <gloss target="#t_Brit1">Brit</gloss> HC visited the <gloss
                        target="#t_FonMin1">FonMin</gloss> half an hour before my own interview.
                        <persName corresp="#p_KCSM1">Zafrulla</persName>’s comments to him, while
                    not so specific as his statements <pb facs="0168" n="1218" xml:id="pg_1218"/> to
                    me, followed the same gen line of a favorable reaction to the proposal from
                    Whitehall in Wash.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WAM1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Warren</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
